d<br>{{nowrap|[[Flash Morgan Webster]] & [[Mark Andrews (wrestler)|Mark Andrews]]}}<br>and<br>Gallus<br>{{small|([[Mark Coffey]] and [[Wolfgang (wrestler)|Wolfgang]])}}\n|[[NXT UK Tag Team Championship]]\n|1\n|There have only been three reigns between three teams thus far.\n|-\n|9\n|[[Perro Aguayo]] & [[Gran Hamada]]\n|[[WWF Intercontinental Tag Team Championship]]\n|1\n|This was the only reign for the title.\n|-\n|}\n\n====By wrestler====\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! #\n! Champion\n! Title\n! # of Reigns\n! Notes\n|-\n|1\n|[[Edge (wrestler)|Edge]]\n|[[World Tag Team Championship (WWE)|World Tag Team Championship]]\n|12\n|During his first seven reigns, the title was known as the WWF World Tag Team Championship. During his eighth reign, the title was known as the WWE Tag Team Championship. During his following four reigns, the title was known as the World Tag Team Championship. It was also simultaneously known as the Unified WWE Tag Team Championship during his 12th reign.\n|-\n|2\n|[[Booker T (wrestler)|Booker T]]\n|[[WCW World Tag Team Championship]]\n|11\n|\n|-\n|3\n|[[Dr. Jerry Graham]]\n|[[WWWF United States Tag Team Championship]]\n|6\n|During his first five reigns, the title was known as the NWA United States Tag Team Championship.\n|-\n|4\n|[[Seth Rollins]]\n|[[WWE Raw Tag Team Championship]]\n|6\n|\n|-\n|5\n|[[Big E (wrestler)|Big E]]\n|[[WWE SmackDown Tag Team Championship]]\n|5\n|\n|-\n|6\n|[[Kyle O'Reilly]]\n|[[NXT Tag Team Championship]]\n|3\n|\n|-\n|7\n|[[Newton Tattrie|Geto Mongol]]\n|[[WWF International Tag Team Championship]]\n|3\n|During all three of his reigns, the title was known as the WWWF International Tag Team Championship.\n|-\n|8\n|[[Mark Andrews (wrestler)|Mark Andrews]], [[Mark Coffey]], [[James Drake (wrestler)|James Drake]], [[Zack Gibson]], [[Flash Morgan Webster]], and [[Wolfgang (wrestler)|Wolfgang]]\n|[[NXT UK Tag Team Championship]]\n|1\n|There have only been three reigns between three teams thus far.\n|-\n|-\n|9\n|[[Perro Aguayo]] and [[Gran Hamada]]\n|[[WWF Intercontinental Tag Team Championship]]\n|1\n|This was the only reign for the title.\n|-\n|}\n\n===Female===\nThe following lists shows the wrestlers with the most reigns for each tag team championship created and/or promoted by WWE.\n\n====By team====\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! #\n! Champion\n! Title\n! # of Reigns\n! Notes\n|-\n|1\n|[[The Glamour Girls]]<br>{{small|([[Judy Martin (wrestler)|Judy Martin]] and [[Leilani Kai]])}}\n|[[WWF Women's Tag Team Championship]]\n|2\n|\n|-\n|2\n|[[Alexa Bliss]] & [[Nikki Cross]]\n|[[WWE Women's Tag Team Championship]]\n|2\n|\n|}\n\n====By wrestler====\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! #\n! Champion\n! Title\n! # of Reigns\n! Notes\n|-\n|1\n|[[Judy Martin (wrestler)|Judy Martin]], [[Leilani Kai]], and [[Velvet McIntyre]]\n|[[WWF Women's Tag Team Championship]]\n|2\n|\n|-\n|2\n|[[Alexa Bliss]] and [[Nikki Cross]] \n|[[WWE Women's Tag Team Championship]]\n|2\n|\n|-\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[World championships in WWE]]\n* [[Women's championships in WWE]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{WWE}}\n\n[[Category:WWE tag team championships| ]]\n[[Category:Tag team wrestling championships]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Listing of WWE tag team championships}}\n{{redirect|WWE Tag Team Championship|the championship that briefly went by this name in 2002|World Tag Team Championship (WWE)|the championship that went by this name from 2002\u20132009 and 2010\u20132016|WWE Raw Tag Team Championship}}\n[[WWE]] (formerly the WWF, WWWF, and its predecessor, [[Capitol Wrestling]]) has maintained at least one primary tag team championship for its male performers since 1958 (except for a two year interim between 1967 and 1969). Whenever [[WWE brand extension|brand division]] has been implemented, separate primary tag team titles have been created or allocated for each brand. \n\nFor their female performers, a tag team championship existed between 1983 and 1989. The title was abandoned in 1989 due to lack of depth in the division. For many years, the women's division lacked a tag team championship, largely in part due to not having enough female performers, that is until 2019, when WWE introduced a new women's tag team championship.\n\n==Overview of titles==\n===Male===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! #\n! Name\n! Years\n|-\n|1\n|[[WWWF United States Tag Team Championship]]\n|1958 \u2013 1967 (became WWWF property in 1963)\n|-\n|2\n|[[WWF International Tag Team Championship]]\n|1969 \u2013 1971, 1985\n|-\n|3\n|[[World Tag Team Championship (WWE)|World Tag Team Championship]]\n|1971 \u2013 2010\n|-\n|4\n|[[WWF Intercontinental Tag Team Championship]]\n|1991\n|-\n|5\n|[[WCW World Tag Team Championship]]\n|1975 \u2013 2001 (became WWF property in 2001)\n|-\n|6\n|[[WWE Raw Tag Team Championship]]\n|2002 \u2013 present\n|-\n|7\n|[[NXT Tag Team Championship]]\n|2013 \u2013 present\n|-\n|8\n|[[WWE SmackDown Tag Team Championship]]\n|2016 \u2013 present\n|-\n|9\n|[[NXT UK Tag Team Championship]]\n|2018 \u2013 present\n|}\n\n===Female===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! #\n! Name\n! Years\n|-\n|1\n|[[WWF Women's Tag Team Championship]]\n|1983 \u2013 1989\n|-\n|2\n|[[WWE Women's Tag Team Championship]]\n|2019 \u2013 present\n|}\n\n==History==\n===Male===\n[[File:The New Day WWE Tag Team Champions Raw April 2016.jpg|thumb|225px|[[The New Day (wrestling)|The New Day]] are two-time [[WWE Raw Tag Team Championship|Raw Tag Team Champions]] and five-time [[WWE SmackDown Tag Team Championship|SmackDown Tag Team Champions]]; their second reign as Raw Tag Team Champions is the longest reign for any primary tag team championship in WWE history at 483 days]]\n[[Capitol Wrestling]] set up its first tag team championship, the [[WWWF United States Tag Team Championship|NWA United States Tag Team Championship]] in 1958.  When Capitol seceded from the [[National Wrestling Alliance]] in 1963 and became the [[History of WWE#World Wide Wrestling Federation|World Wide Wrestling Federation]] (WWWF), the championship became the WWWF United States Tag Team Championship. In 1967, [[WWE Championship|WWWF World Heavyweight Champion]] [[Bruno Sammartino]] teamed with [[Spiros Arion]] to win the belts. Due to Sammartino being the world champion, the team vacated the tag titles which were then abandoned.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wrestling-titles.com/wwe/wwf-us-t.html|title=United States Tag Team Title (Capitol/WWWF)|website=Wrestling-Titles.com|language=en|access-date=2017-10-20}}</ref>\n\nFor two years, the WWWF had no tag team championship until The Rising Suns ([[Toru Tanaka]] and [[Mitsu Arakawa]]) arrived in the promotion in September 1969 with the [[WWF International Tag Team Championship|WWWF International Tag Team Championship]] which they claimed to have won in a tournament in [[Tokyo]] in June of that year. This became the WWWF's tag team title until 1971, mostly being held by [[Geeto Mongol|The Mongols]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wrestling-titles.com/us/pa/w/studio/wwwf-in-t.html|title=WWWF/WWF International Tag Team Title|website=Wrestling-Titles.com|language=en|access-date=2017-10-20}}</ref> When they left the WWWF, taking the titles with them, the promotion established their own original world tag team championship, the [[World Tag Team Championship (WWE)|WWWF World Tag Team Championship]]. In 1979, the promotion became the [[History of WWE#World Wrestling Federation|World Wrestling Federation]] (WWF) and the tag titles were shortened to WWF Tag Team Championship until 1983 when they were renamed WWF World Tag Team Championship. \n\nBy 1988, wrestling magazine ''[[Pro Wrestling Illustrated]]'' was calling for  the establishment of a secondary WWF Intercontinental Tag Team Championship (modelled on the [[WCW United States Tag Team Championship]]) due to the glut of tag team competition in the promotion.<ref name=pwi>\"Too much talent - It's Time For A WWF Intercontinental Tag Team Championship\" - [[Pro Wrestling Illustrated]] December 1998</ref> This never took place, but in 1991, WWF-affiliated promotion [[Universal Lucha Libre|UWF Japan]] introduced the [[WWF Intercontinental Tag Team Championship]], claimed by the team of [[Perro Aguayo]] and [[Gran Hamada]]. This title was abandoned when the affiliation ended later that same year.<ref name=ictag>{{cite web|title=10 championships you never knew existed in WWE|url=http://www.wwe.com/classics/classic-lists/10-titles-you-never-knew-existed|publisher=[[WWE]]}}</ref>  Similarly, back in May 1985, [[Tatsumi Fujinami]] and [[Kengo Kimura]] beat [[Dick Murdoch]] and [[Adrian Adonis]] in a tournament final in Japan for a revival of the old International Tag Team Title of 1969\u20131971, only for the title to be abandoned again when New Japan and the WWF fell out in October 1985.\n\nIn 2001, the [[WWE#Acquisition of WCW and ECW|WWF bought rival company World Championship Wrestling (WCW)]], acquiring the [[WCW World Tag Team Championship]], among other titles, which was defended on WWF programming until that year's [[Survivor Series (2001)|Survivor Series]], where the WCW World Tag Team Championship was unified into the WWF World Tag Team Championship.<ref name=\"world\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestling-titles.com/wwe/wwe-world-t.html|title=WWWF/WWF/WWE World Tag Team Title|author=|date=|website=Wrestling-Titles.com|accessdate=19 March 2018}}</ref>\n\t\t \t\nAfter WWF's initial [[WWE brand extension|brand extension]] in the spring of 2002 and the renaming of the company as [[History of WWE#World Wrestling Entertainment/WWE|World Wrestling Entertainment]] (WWE), the tag titles became the WWE Tag Team Championship and champions [[Billy and Chuck]] were drafted to the [[SmackDown (WWE brand)|SmackDown]] brand. That summer, however, [[The Un-Americans]] ([[Christian Cage|Christian]] and [[Lance Storm]]) would win the championship and shortly thereafter transfer it to the [[Raw (WWE brand)|Raw]] brand where it was later renamed the World Tag Team Championship, effectively leaving the SmackDown brand without a tag team title. As a result, then-[[Professional wrestling authority figures#General managers|SmackDown General Manager]] [[Stephanie McMahon]] introduced [[WWE Raw Tag Team Championship|a new WWE Tag Team Championship]] and commissioned it to be the tag team title for the SmackDown brand.<ref name=\"raw\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestling-titles.com/wwe/wwe-t.html|title=WWE Tag Team Championship|author=|date=|website=Wrestling-Titles.com|accessdate=19 March 2018}}</ref>\n\t\t\t\nBoth titles were [[Championship unification|unified]] in 2009 and were collectively referred to as the \"Unified WWE Tag Team Championship\" while officially remaining independently active until the World Tag Team Championship was formally decommissioned in 2010,<ref name=\"world\" /><ref name=\"raw\" /> leaving the newer title as WWE's only tag team championship. As a result of the [[2016 WWE draft|2016 draft]], the championship became exclusive to Raw and was renamed the Raw Tag Team Championship, and SmackDown created the [[WWE SmackDown Tag Team Championship|SmackDown Tag Team Championship]] as a counterpart title.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestling-titles.com/wwe/wwe-sd-t.html|title=WWE Smackdown Tag Team Title|author=|date=|website=Wrestling-Titles.com|accessdate=19 March 2018}}</ref> In addition, WWE's former [[Farm team|developmental territory]] [[NXT (WWE brand)|NXT]] established the [[NXT Tag Team Championship]] in January 2013, which became one of WWE's three main titles for male tag teams in September 2019 when NXT became recognized as WWE's third major brand. Another title, the [[NXT UK Tag Team Championship]], debuted for NXT's sister brand [[NXT UK (WWE brand)|NXT UK]] in 2019, but is recognized as being a step below the other three. The Raw, SmackDown, NXT, and NXT UK tag team titles are WWE's four currently active tag team championships for its male performers.\n\n===Female===\nPrior to 1983, the WWF did not have a tag team championship for their women's division. In 1983, the team of [[Velvet McIntyre]] and [[Vickie Otis|Princess Victoria]] joined the WWF and were already the reigning [[NWA Women's World Tag Team Championship|NWA Women's World Tag Team Champions]]. The WWF had since withdrawn from the NWA, which owned the championship, thus McIntyre and Victoria were instead recognized as the first [[WWF Women's Tag Team Championship|WWF Women's Tag Team Champions]]. The championship continued until 1989 when the promotion abandoned the titles with [[The Glamour Girls]] ([[Leilani Kai]] and [[Judy Martin (wrestler)|Judy Martin]]) as the final champions. The titles were abandoned due to lack of depth in the division.\n\nThe promotion would go without a women's tag team championship for many years. Talk of reviving the titles began circulating in 2012, when a WWE.com article was posted in favor of resurrecting the titles. Female performers were also in favor of adding a women's tag team championship, but it was not until 2018 when the titles became a reality. Online speculation began when WWE announced their first all female event [[WWE Evolution|Evolution]] for October, but the titles did not appear or were announced. However, on the December 24 episode of ''[[WWE Raw|Monday Night Raw]]'', WWE Chairman [[Vince McMahon]] officially announced that a new [[WWE Women's Tag Team Championship]] would debut in 2019 (and would not carry the lineage of the original title). [[The Boss 'n' Hug Connection]] ([[Bayley (wrestler)|Bayley]] and [[Sasha Banks]]) became the inaugural champions at [[Elimination Chamber (2019)|Elimination Chamber]] in February. It was also revealed that the titles would be defended across the Raw, SmackDown, and NXT brands (due to none of the brands having enough women to have their own championship).\n\n==Longest championship reigns==\n===Male===\n====Top 10 tag team championship reigns====\nThe following list shows the top 10 tag team championship reigns in WWE history.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! #\n! Team\n! Title\n! Reign\n! Length<br>(days)\n! Notes\n|-\n|1\n|[[The New Day (wrestling)|The New Day]]<br>{{small|([[Big E (wrestler)|Big E]], [[Kofi Kingston]], and [[Xavier Woods]])}}\n|[[WWE Raw Tag Team Championship]]\n|2\n|483\n|They won the title as the WWE Tag Team Championship, but midway through this reign, it was renamed to Raw Tag Team Championship following the reintroduction of the [[WWE brand extension]] when the title became exclusive to [[Raw (WWE brand)|Raw]]. All three members were recognized as champion under the [[Freebird Rule]].\n|-\n|2\n|[[Demolition (professional wrestling)|Demolition]]<br>{{small|([[Ax (wrestler)|Ax]] and [[Smash (wrestler)|Smash]])}}\n|[[World Tag Team Championship (WWE)|World Tag Team Championship]]\n|1\n|478\n|During this reign, the title was known as the WWF World Tag Team Championship.\n|-\n|3\n|[[The Fabulous Kangaroos]]<br>{{small|([[Al Costello]] and [[Roy Heffernan]])}}\n|[[WWWF United States Tag Team Championship]]\n|3\n|409\n|During this reign, the title was known as the NWA United States Tag Team Championship.\n|-\n|4\n|[[The Valiant Brothers]]<br>{{small|([[Jimmy Valiant]] and [[Johnny Valiant]])}}\n|[[World Tag Team Championship (WWE)|World Tag Team Championship]]\n|1\n|370\n|During this reign, the title was known as the WWWF World Tag Team Championship.\n|-\n|5\n|[[Geeto Mongol|The Mongols]]<br>{{small|([[Nikolai Volkoff|Bepo]] and [[Newton Tattrie|Geto]])}}\n|[[WWF International Tag Team Championship]]\n|1\n|368\n|During this reign, the title was known as the WWWF International Tag Team Championship.\n|-\n|6\n|[[The Ascension (professional wrestling)|The Ascension]]<br>{{small|([[Konnor (wrestler)|Konnor]] and [[Viktor (wrestler)|Viktor]])}}\n|[[NXT Tag Team Championship]]\n|1\n|364\n|WWE recognizes The Ascension's reign as lasting 344 days due to [[Broadcast delay|tape delay]].\n|-\n|7\n|[[Mr Fuji]] and [[Professor Tanaka]]\n|[[World Tag Team Championship (WWE)|World Tag Team Championship]]\n|1\n|337\n|During this reign, the title was known as the WWWF World Tag Team Championship.\n|-\n|8\n|[[Paul London]] and [[Brian Kendrick]]\n|[[WWE Raw Tag Team Championship]]\n|1\n|331\n|During this reign, the title was known as the WWE Tag Team Championship.<br>WWE recognizes London and Kendrick's reign as lasting 334 days due to [[Broadcast delay|tape delay]].\n|-\n|9\n|{{nowrap|[[Dr. Jerry Graham]] and [[Luke Graham (wrestler)|Luke Graham]]}}\n|[[WWWF United States Tag Team Championship]]\n|1\n|321\n|\n|-\n|10\n|[[The British Bulldogs]]<br>{{small|([[Dynamite Kid]] and [[Davey Boy Smith]])}}\n|[[World Tag Team Championship (WWE)|World Tag Team Championship]]\n|1\n|294\n|During this reign, the title was known as the WWF World Tag Team Championship.\n|}\n\n====Specific record for each championship====\nThe following list shows the longest reigning champion for each tag team championship created and/or promoted by WWE, with the exception of the [[WWF Intercontinental Tag Team Championship]]. The team of [[Perro Aguayo]] and [[Gran Hamada]] won the inaugural championship on January 7, 1991, but during their reign later that year, the title was abandoned. The date of abandonment, and consequently their reign length, is unknown.\n\nTitles are listed in order of creation.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Title\n! Champion\n! Reign\n! Dates held\n! Length<br>(days)\n! Notes\n|-\n|[[WWWF United States Tag Team Championship]]\n|[[The Fabulous Kangaroos]]<br>{{small|([[Al Costello]] and [[Roy Heffernan]])}}\n|3rd\n|November 28, 1960 \u2013 January 11, 1962\n|409\n|During this reign, the title was known as the NWA United States Tag Team Championship.\n|-\n|[[WWF International Tag Team Championship]]\n|[[Geeto Mongol|The Mongols]]<br>{{small|([[Nikolai Volkoff|Bepo]] and [[Newton Tattrie|Geto]])}}\n|1st\n|June 15, 1970 \u2013 June 18, 1971\n|368\n|During this reign, the title was known as the WWWF International Tag Team Championship.\n|-\n|[[World Tag Team Championship (WWE)|World Tag Team Championship]]\n|[[Demolition (professional wrestling)|Demolition]]<br>{{small|([[Ax (wrestler)|Ax]] and [[Smash (wrestler)|Smash]])}}\n|1st\n|May 27, 1988 \u2013 July 18, 1989\n|478\n|During this reign, the title was known as the WWF World Tag Team Championship.\n|-\n|[[WCW World Tag Team Championship]]\n|[[Doom (professional wrestling)|Doom]]<br>{{small|([[Butch Reed]] and [[Ron Simmons]])}}\n|1st\n|May 19, 1990 \u2013 February 24, 1991\n|281\n|The title was owned by [[World Championship Wrestling]] (WCW) at this time. Originally known as the NWA World Tag Team Championship, during this reign, it was renamed to WCW World Tag Team Championship due to issues between the NWA and WCW.\n|-\n|[[WWE Raw Tag Team Championship]]\n|[[The New Day (wrestling)|The New Day]]<br>{{small|([[Big E (wrestler)|Big E]], [[Kofi Kingston]], and [[Xavier Woods]])}}\n|2nd\n|April 23, 2015 \u2013 December 18, 2016\n|483\n|The New Day won the title as the WWE Tag Team Championship, but midway through this reign, it was renamed to Raw Tag Team Championship following the reintroduction of the [[WWE brand extension]] when the title became exclusive to [[Raw (WWE brand)|Raw]]. All three members were recognized as champion under the [[Freebird Rule]].\n|-\n|[[NXT Tag Team Championship]]\n|[[The Ascension (professional wrestling)|The Ascension]]<br>{{small|([[Konnor (wrestler)|Konnor]] and [[Viktor (wrestler)|Viktor]])}}\n|1st\n|September 12, 2013 \u2013 September 11, 2014\n|364\n|WWE recognizes The Ascension's reign as lasting 344 days (October 2, 2013 \u2013 September 11, 2014) due to [[Broadcast delay|tape delay]].\n|-\n|[[WWE SmackDown Tag Team Championship]]\n|[[The Usos]]<br>{{small|(Jey Uso and Jimmy Uso)}}\n|3rd\n|October 8, 2017 \u2013 April 8, 2018\n|182\n|\n|-\n|[[NXT UK Tag Team Championship]]\n|{{nowrap|[[James Drake (wrestler)|James Drake]] & [[Zack Gibson]]}}\n|1st\n|January 12, 2019 \u2013 August 31, 2019\n|231\n|WWE recognizes Gibson and Drake's reign as lasting 230 days.\n|}\n\n===Female===\nDue to the short length of both championships, only the specific record for each is shown.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! #\n! Champion\n! Title\n! Reign\n! Dates held\n! Length<br>(days)\n! Notes\n|-\n|1\n|{{nowrap|[[The Glamour Girls]]}}<br />{{nowrap|{{small|([[Judy Martin (wrestler)|Judy Martin]] and [[Leilani Kai]])}}}}\n|[[WWF Women's Tag Team Championship]]\n|1\n|August 1, 1985 \u2013 January 24, 1988\n|906\n|\n|-\n|2\n|{{nowrap|The Kabuki Warriors}}<br>{{small|([[Asuka (wrestler)|Asuka]] and [[Kairi Sane]])}}\n|[[WWE Women's Tag Team Championship]]\n|1\n|October 6 , 2019 \u2013 April 04, 2020\n|171 or 172\n||The event that they lost the title was taped across two days, and it is currently not known which date they lost the titles. WWE recognizes The Kabuki Warrior's reign as lasting 181 days due to [[Broadcast delay|tape delay]].\n|-\n|}\n\n==Most championship reigns==\n===Male===\nThe following lists shows the wrestlers with the most reigns for each tag team championship created and/or promoted by WWE.\n====By team====\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! #\n! Champion\n! Title\n! # of Reigns\n! Notes\n|-\n|1\n|[[Harlem Heat]]<br>{{small|([[Booker T (wrestler)|Booker T]] and [[Stevie Ray]])}}\n|[[WCW World Tag Team Championship]]\n|10\n|\n|-\n|2\n|[[The Dudley Boyz]]<br>{{small|([[Bubba Ray Dudley]] and [[D-Von Dudley]])}}\n|[[World Tag Team Championship (WWE)|World Tag Team Championship]]\n|8\n|During their first six reigns, the title was known as the WWF World Tag Team Championship. \n|-\n|3\n|[[The New Day (professional wrestling)|The New Day]]\n|[[WWE SmackDown Tag Team Championship]]\n|7\n|During their first three reigns, [[Big E (wrestler)|Big E]], [[Kofi Kingston]], and [[Xavier Woods]] were all recognized as champion under the [[Freebird Rule]]. During their fourth reign, only Big E and Woods were recognized as champion as Kingston was the reigning [[WWE Champion]], while for their fifth reign, only Big E an